# Agent Sandbox on OpenShift — Domain Knowledge

## What is Agent Sandbox?

kubernetes-sigs/agent-sandbox is a Kubernetes SIG-Apps project that provides
Custom Resource Definitions (CRDs) for managing isolated, stateful, singleton
workloads — specifically designed for AI coding agents that execute untrusted code.

Project: https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/agent-sandbox
Version: v0.2.1

## CRD Reference

### Sandbox (core)
- apiVersion: agents.x-k8s.io/v1alpha1
- Creates a single pod + headless Service + optional PVCs
- Pod spec goes under spec.podTemplate.spec (standard PodSpec)
- Metadata/annotations go under spec.podTemplate.metadata

### SandboxTemplate (extension)
- apiVersion: extensions.agents.x-k8s.io/v1alpha1
- Reusable template for creating sandboxes via SandboxClaim
- Same spec as Sandbox plus spec.networkPolicy for per-sandbox NetworkPolicy

### SandboxWarmPool (extension)
- apiVersion: extensions.agents.x-k8s.io/v1alpha1
- Pre-warms N sandbox pods from a SandboxTemplate
- spec.replicas: number of warm pods
- spec.sandboxTemplateRef.name: must match a SandboxTemplate in same namespace

### SandboxClaim (extension)
- apiVersion: extensions.agents.x-k8s.io/v1alpha1
- Claims a sandbox from a WarmPool (instant) or creates one from template
- spec.sandboxTemplateRef.name: must match a SandboxTemplate
- spec.lifecycle.shutdownPolicy: "Retain" (keep after release) or "Delete"

## NetworkPolicy in SandboxTemplate

IMPORTANT: As of agent-sandbox v0.2.1, the SandboxTemplate's spec.networkPolicy
section is stored but the controller does NOT auto-create Kubernetes NetworkPolicy
resources from it. You must create a NetworkPolicy manually in the same namespace.
This may be fixed in a future release.

Recommended deny-all with DNS exception:
```yaml
networkPolicy:
  ingress:
    - from:
        - namespaceSelector:
            matchLabels:
              kubernetes.io/metadata.name: <workspace-namespace>
  egress:
    - ports:
        - protocol: UDP
          port: 53
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 53
```

This blocks:
- All outbound traffic (no data exfiltration)
- Access to the Kubernetes API server
- Communication with other sandbox pods
- Only DNS resolution is allowed

## RuntimeClass Options

| Platform | RuntimeClass | Isolation |
|----------|-------------|-----------|
| AWS (OpenShift) | kata-remote | Peer pod — dedicated EC2 VM |
| Bare metal (OpenShift) | kata | Kata Container — lightweight VM |
| GKE | gvisor | gVisor — user-space kernel |
| Any | (omit field) | Standard container — no VM isolation |

On AWS with OpenShift Sandboxed Containers, use `kata-remote`. This runs each
sandbox inside a dedicated EC2 instance via the peer pods architecture.

Kata annotations for tuning (in podTemplate.metadata.annotations):
- io.katacontainers.config.hypervisor.default_vcpus: "2"
- io.katacontainers.config.hypervisor.default_memory: "4096"

AWS peer-pods ONLY annotations (remove on bare metal or GKE):
- io.katacontainers.config.hypervisor.machine_type: "t3.medium"
  Forces the EC2 instance type. Required because the peer-pods AMI uses
  TPM 2.0, which older instance families (t2) do not support.
- io.kubernetes.cri-o.userns-mode: ""

## OpenShift SCC Requirements

On OpenShift, the SandboxTemplate uses runAsUser: 10001 to match the container
image's non-root user. OpenShift's restricted-v2 SCC rejects UIDs outside the
namespace's auto-assigned range. You must grant `anyuid` SCC:
  oc adm policy add-scc-to-user anyuid -z agent-sandbox-controller -n agent-sandbox-system
  oc adm policy add-scc-to-user anyuid -z default -n <sandbox-namespace>
This is NOT needed on vanilla Kubernetes.

## Security Settings Rationale

- automountServiceAccountToken: false — prevents sandbox from accessing K8s API
- runAsNonRoot: true — prevents root escalation inside the container
- runAsUser: 10001 — matches the non-root user in the mcp-skills image
- Resource limits (2 CPU, 4Gi) — prevents resource abuse / crypto mining
- NetworkPolicy deny-all — prevents data exfiltration and lateral movement

## OpenShift Sandboxed Containers Setup

To enable Kata runtime on OpenShift:

1. Install the operator:
   - Package: sandboxed-containers-operator
   - Channel: stable
   - Namespace: openshift-sandboxed-containers-operator

2. Create KataConfig:
   ```yaml
   apiVersion: kataconfiguration.openshift.io/v1
   kind: KataConfig
   metadata:
     name: cluster-kataconfig
   spec:
     enablePeerPods: true  # Required for AWS
   ```

3. For AWS, also need:
   - peer-pods-secret (AWS credentials)
   - peer-pods-cm (region, VPC, subnet, security groups)
   - Security group rules for ports 15150 and 9000

4. KataConfig triggers node reboots (10-60 min)
5. RuntimeClass `kata-remote` becomes available after installation

## Troubleshooting

- "RuntimeClass not found": Kata not installed yet. Sandbox will fail to
  schedule. Either install Kata or remove runtimeClassName from the template.
- "unable to validate against any security context constraint": Grant anyuid
  SCC to both the controller SA and the default SA in the sandbox namespace.
- "UnsupportedOperation: The t2.medium instance type does not support an AMI
  with TPM version v2.0": Add the machine_type annotation to force t3.medium.
  This only affects AWS peer-pods.
- "sandbox pod pending": Check events with `oc get events -n <namespace>`.
  Common cause: insufficient resources or RuntimeClass not available.
- "warm pool pods not starting": Verify the SandboxTemplate exists in the
  same namespace as the WarmPool. Names must match exactly.
- "curl works from sandbox" (network not blocked): The SandboxTemplate's
  networkPolicy is not auto-applied. Create a Kubernetes NetworkPolicy manually.
- Peer pods on AWS: If sandbox pods are stuck in ContainerCreating, check
  the cloud-api-adaptor logs in openshift-sandboxed-containers-operator namespace.
